\begin_layout Standard
In this note I show the problems of convolution formula in baryon case and
 I give a short conclusion in the end.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The convolution formula in meson loop condition is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{x}^{1}dy\frac{1}{y}f(y,\xi,t)H_{q}(\frac{x}{y},\frac{\xi}{y},t),\quad y & >x>\xi\\
\int_{\xi}^{1}dy\frac{1}{y}f(y,\xi,t)H_{q}(\frac{x}{y},\frac{\xi}{y},t),\quad y & >\xi>x\\
\int_{-\xi}^{\xi}dy\frac{1}{2\xi}f(y,\xi,t)\frac{\xi}{\pi y}\int_{s_{0}}^{\infty}ds\frac{Im\Phi(\frac{\frac{x}{\xi}+1}{2},\frac{\frac{y}{\xi}+1}{2},s)}{s-t+i\epsilon}\quad\xi & >\{y,|x|\}\\
\int_{-x}^{1}dy\frac{1}{y}f(y,\xi,t)H_{q}(\frac{x}{y},\frac{\xi}{y},t),\quad- & \xi>x>-1
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where the 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\frac{k^{+}}{P^{+}}-\xi$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The relationship of y and x in the formula is
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename pic/convolution.pdf

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In meson loop the y and x in convolution formula
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now with new definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\frac{k^{+}}{P^{+}}$
\end_inset

, the intermediate particle is octet baryon and their momentum is 
\begin_inset Formula $1-y\pm\xi$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have same relation as the picture in Fig2 only replace the 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 to be 
\begin_inset Formula $1-y$
\end_inset

.
 So if we replace the y in convolution formula of meson loop with 
\begin_inset Formula $1-y$
\end_inset

, we can still use the same convolution formula upside.
 The equation becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{x}^{1}d(1-y)\frac{1}{1-y}f(y,\xi,t)H_{q}(\frac{x}{1-y},\frac{\xi}{1-y},t),\quad1-y & >x>\xi\\
\int_{\xi}^{1}d(1-y)\frac{1}{1-y}f(y,\xi,t)H_{q}(\frac{x}{1-y},\frac{\xi}{1-y},t),\quad1-y & >\xi>x\\
\int_{-\xi}^{\xi}d(1-y)\frac{1}{2\xi}f(y,\xi,t)\frac{1}{\pi}\frac{\xi}{1-y}\int_{s_{0}}^{\infty}ds\frac{Im\Phi(\frac{\frac{x}{\xi}+1}{2},\frac{\frac{1-y}{\xi}+1}{2},s)}{s-t+i\epsilon}\quad\xi & >\{1-y,|x|\}\\
\int_{-x}^{1}d(1-y)\frac{1}{1-y}f(y,\xi,t)H_{q}(\frac{x}{1-y},\frac{\xi}{1-y},t),\quad- & \xi>x>-1
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Noticed that in the splitting function I still use 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 This is because the splitting function here describe the meson with momentum
 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $f(1-y)$
\end_inset

 is still a meson with momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $1-y$
\end_inset

 while now the momentum of baryon is 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(x)$
\end_inset

 describe baryon with momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 should satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(1-y)=f(y)$
\end_inset

 because the baryon with momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $1-y$
\end_inset

 and the meson with momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are corresponding.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In meson loop condition the range of 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\frac{k^{+}}{P^{+}}-\xi$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $[-\xi,1]$
\end_inset

, so in baryon case the range of 
\begin_inset Formula $1-y$
\end_inset

, where the 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\frac{k^{+}}{P^{+}}$
\end_inset

, should also be in 
\begin_inset Formula $[-\xi,1]$
\end_inset

 and the range of 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\frac{k^{+}}{P^{+}}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1+\xi]$
\end_inset

.
 For most diagrams in Fig1, the range of 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\frac{k^{+}}{P^{+}}$
\end_inset

 is in 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1+\xi]$
\end_inset

.
 However in additional KR diagram with left vertex which is diagram g and
 diagram u, the range of 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\frac{k^{+}}{P^{+}}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $[-2\xi,1-\xi]$
\end_inset

 and the range of 
\begin_inset Formula $1-y$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $[\xi,1+2\xi]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the difference is the range of 
\begin_inset Formula $1-y$
\end_inset

, one can still use the formula just change the range of integral which
 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{x}^{1+2\xi}d(1-y)\frac{1}{1-y}f(y,\xi,t)H_{q}(\frac{x}{1-y},\frac{\xi}{1-y},t),\quad1-y & >x>\xi\\
\int_{\xi}^{1+2\xi}d(1-y)\frac{1}{1-y}f(y,\xi,t)H_{q}(\frac{x}{1-y},\frac{\xi}{1-y},t),\quad1-y & >\xi>x\\
\int_{-x}^{1+2\xi}d(1-y)\frac{1}{1-y}f(y,\xi,t)H_{q}(\frac{x}{1-y},\frac{\xi}{1-y},t),\quad- & \xi>x>-1
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now I'll show the problem in this simple method.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can check the 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 independence of electromagnetic form factor from GPD.
 For other diagrams, the form factor is, where I replace 
\begin_inset Formula $1-y$
\end_inset

 with y to make it easier to write.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{-1}^{1}dxH(x,\xi,t) & =\int_{\xi}^{1}dx\int_{x}^{1}dy\frac{1}{y}f(1-y,\xi,t)H_{q}(\frac{x}{y},\frac{\xi}{y},t)\\
 & +\int_{-\xi}^{\xi}dx\int_{\xi}^{1}dy\frac{1}{y}f(1-y,\xi,t)H_{q}(\frac{x}{y},\frac{\xi}{y},t)\\
 & +\int_{-\xi}^{\xi}dx\int_{-\xi}^{\xi}d(y)\frac{1}{2\xi}f(1-y,\xi,t)\frac{\xi}{\pi y}\int_{s_{0}}^{\infty}ds\frac{Im\Phi(\frac{\frac{x}{\xi}+1}{2},\frac{\frac{y}{\xi}+1}{2},s)}{s-t+i\epsilon}\\
 & +\int_{-1}^{-\xi}dx\int_{-x}^{1}dy\frac{1}{y}f(1-y,\xi,t)H_{q}(\frac{x}{y},\frac{\xi}{y},t)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is almost the same as meson loop condition.
 The first term 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\xi}^{1}dx\int_{x}^{1}dy\frac{1}{y}f(1-y,\xi,t)H_{q}(\frac{x}{y},\frac{\xi}{y},t)$
\end_inset

 will be transformed like this when we prove the 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 independence.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{\xi}^{1}dx\int_{x}^{1}dy\frac{1}{y}f(1-y,\xi,t)H_{q}(\frac{x}{y},\frac{\xi}{y},t) & =\int_{\xi}^{1}dy\int_{\xi}^{y}dx\frac{1}{y}f(1-y,\xi,t)H_{q}(\frac{x}{y},\frac{\xi}{y},t)\\
 & =\int_{\xi}^{1}dyf(1-y,\xi,t)\int_{\frac{\xi}{y}}^{1}d(\frac{x}{y})H_{q}(\frac{x}{y},\frac{\xi}{y},t)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For diagram g and u, where the range of y in splitting function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(y,\xi,t)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $[-2\xi,1-\xi]$
\end_inset

, the integral is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{-1}^{1}dxH(x,\xi,t)=\int_{\xi}^{1}dx\int_{x}^{1+2\xi}dy\frac{1}{y}f(1-y,\xi,t)H_{q}(\frac{x}{y},\frac{\xi}{y},t)+\int_{-\xi}^{\xi}dx\int_{\xi}^{1+2\xi}dy\frac{1}{y}f(1-y,\xi,t)H_{q}(\frac{x}{y},\frac{\xi}{y},t)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{\xi}^{1}dx\int_{x}^{1+2\xi}dy\frac{1}{y}f(1-y,\xi,t)H_{q}(\frac{x}{y},\frac{\xi}{y},t) & =\int_{\xi}^{1}dy\int_{\xi}^{y}dx\frac{1}{y}f(1-y,\xi,t)H_{q}(\frac{x}{y},\frac{\xi}{y},t)\\
 & +\int_{1}^{1+2\xi}dy\int_{\xi}^{1}dx\frac{1}{y}f(1-y,\xi,t)H_{q}(\frac{x}{y},\frac{\xi}{y},t)\\
 & =\int_{\xi}^{1}dyf(1-y,\xi,t)\int_{\frac{\xi}{y}}^{1}d(\frac{x}{y})H_{q}(\frac{x}{y},\frac{\xi}{y},t)\\
 & +\int_{1}^{1+2\xi}dyf(1-y,\xi,t)\int_{\frac{\xi}{u}}^{\frac{1}{y}}d(\frac{x}{y})H_{q}(\frac{x}{y},\frac{\xi}{y},t)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{-\xi}^{\xi}dx\int_{\xi}^{1+2\xi}dy\frac{1}{y}f(1-y,\xi,t)H_{q}(\frac{x}{y},\frac{\xi}{y},t) & =\int_{\xi}^{1}dy\int_{-\xi}^{\xi}dx\frac{1}{y}f(1-y,\xi,t)H_{q}(\frac{x}{y},\frac{\xi}{y},t)\\
 & +\int_{1}^{1+2\xi}dy\int_{-\xi}^{\xi}dx\frac{1}{y}f(1-y,\xi,t)H_{q}(\frac{x}{y},\frac{\xi}{y},t)\\
 & =\int_{\xi}^{1}dyf(1-y,\xi,t)\int_{-\frac{\xi}{y}}^{\frac{\xi}{y}}d(\frac{x}{y})H_{q}(\frac{x}{y},\frac{\xi}{y},t)\\
 & +\int_{1}^{1+2\xi}dyf(1-y,\xi,t)\int_{-\frac{\xi}{y}}^{\frac{\xi}{y}}d(\frac{x}{y})H_{q}(\frac{x}{y},\frac{\xi}{y},t)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we can not get 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{-1}^{1}d(\frac{x}{y})H_{q}(\frac{x}{y},\frac{\xi}{y},t)=F(t)$
\end_inset

, instead we will have this term 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{1}^{1+2\xi}dyf(1-y,\xi,t)\int_{-\frac{1}{y}}^{\frac{1}{y}}d(\frac{x}{y})H_{q}(\frac{x}{y},\frac{\xi}{y},t)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Still we can try to prove this.
 But even we prove the 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 independence, the range of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{y}=1-y$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $[1,1+\xi]$
\end_inset

 need physical explain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can do a simple change in the KR additional diagram calculation to change
 the range of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 The contribution of the additional KR diagram is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\Gamma_{(f+g)}^{+} & =\int\frac{d^{4}k}{(2\pi)^{4}}\frac{i}{D_{\phi}(k)}\tilde{F}(k)[\frac{2k^{+}-q^{+}}{2kq-q^{2}}(\tilde{F}(k)-\tilde{F}(k-q))\cancel{k}\gamma_{5}\frac{\cancel{p'}-\cancel{k}+M_{B}}{D_{B}(p'-k)}(\cancel{k}-\cancel{q})\gamma_{5}\nonumber \\
 & +\frac{2k^{+}+q^{+}}{2kq+q^{2}}(\tilde{F}(k+q)-\tilde{F}(k))(\cancel{k}+\cancel{q})\gamma_{5}\frac{\cancel{p}-\cancel{k}+M_{B}}{D_{B}(p-k)}\cancel{k}\gamma_{5}]\delta(y-\frac{k^{+}}{P^{+}})
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The different range of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{y}=1-y$
\end_inset

 is from the first line of eq.1.
 So we can change 
\begin_inset Formula $k->k+q$
\end_inset

 , because the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is variable of integration
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int\frac{d^{4}k}{(2\pi)^{4}}\frac{i}{D_{\phi}(k)}\tilde{F}(k)\frac{2k^{+}-q^{+}}{2kq-q^{2}}(\tilde{F}(k)-\tilde{F}(k-q))\cancel{k}\gamma_{5}\frac{\cancel{p'}-\cancel{k}+M_{B}}{D_{B}(p'-k)}(\cancel{k}-\cancel{q})\gamma_{5}\delta(y-\frac{k^{+}}{P^{+}})\\
=\int\frac{d^{4}k}{(2\pi)^{4}}\frac{i}{D_{\phi}(k+q)}\tilde{F}(k+q)\frac{2k^{+}+q^{+}}{2kq+q^{2}}(\tilde{F}(k+q)-\tilde{F}(k))(\cancel{k}+\cancel{q})\gamma_{5}\frac{\cancel{p}-\cancel{k}+M_{B}}{D_{B}(p-k)}\cancel{k}\gamma_{5}\delta(y-\frac{k^{+}}{P^{+}})
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The new definition is almost same as the old one, only 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 turns to be 
\begin_inset Formula $y+2\xi$
\end_inset

 and now the range of new 
\begin_inset Formula $y'$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1+\xi]$
\end_inset

 which satisfy the convolution formula.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For KR diagram, this change can also be done in another way due to the definitio
n of operator can be changed and we will have different 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(y)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int\frac{d^{4}k}{(2\pi)^{4}}\frac{i}{D_{\phi}(k)}\tilde{F}(k)\frac{2k^{+}-q^{+}}{2kq-q^{2}}(\tilde{F}(k)-\tilde{F}(k-q))\cancel{k}\gamma_{5}\frac{\cancel{p'}-\cancel{k}+M_{B}}{D_{B}(p'-k)}(\cancel{k}-\cancel{q})\gamma_{5}\delta(y-\frac{k^{+}}{P^{+}})\\
=\int\frac{d^{4}k}{(2\pi)^{4}}\frac{i}{D_{\phi}(k)}\tilde{F}(k)\frac{2k^{+}-q^{+}}{2kq-q^{2}}(\tilde{F}(k)-\tilde{F}(k-q))\cancel{k}\gamma_{5}\frac{\cancel{p'}-\cancel{k}+M_{B}}{D_{B}(p'-k)}(\cancel{k}-\cancel{q})\gamma_{5}\delta(y'-\frac{k^{+}}{P^{+}}-2\xi)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then in new definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $y'=y+2\xi\in[0,1+\xi]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But the first moment of splitting function changes in this different definition
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 which should be like asked by the polynomiality of GPD,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{-1}^{1}dyyf(y,\xi,t)=A(t)+(2\xi)^{2}D(t)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and the old definition satisfy this.
 The new definition will contain a 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 term which looks like
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{-1}^{1}dy'y'f(y',\xi,t)=A(t)+(2\xi)^{2}D(t)+(\xi)C(t)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Besides, the result of gravitational form factor from Yusupujiang is close
 to this definition of the first moment of splitting function from KR diagram
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{-1}^{1}dyyf(y,\xi,t)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
while the same equation in rainbow diagram is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{-1}^{1}dy(1-y)f(y,\xi,t)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means the particle couple to photon in KR vertex is meson instead of
 baryon and maybe the convolution formula need to be changed.
 However, in this condition, the range of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $[-2\xi,1-\xi]$
\end_inset

 in KR additional diagram, and 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1+\xi]$
\end_inset

 in normal KR diagram which do not satisfy the convolution formula in meson
 loop.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In conclusion, the problems are,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The range of the variable of integration in convolution formula,
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in meson loop and 
\begin_inset Formula $1-y$
\end_inset

 in baryon loop, should be in 
\begin_inset Formula $[-\xi,1]$
\end_inset

.
 If bigger than 1, we can not get the polynomiality of GPD, if smaller than
 
\begin_inset Formula $-\xi$
\end_inset

, it's hard to find the input.
 And now in the KR additional diagram with vertex in the left part which
 is diagram g and diagram u the range of 
\begin_inset Formula $1-y$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $[\xi,1+2\xi]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If we simply change the 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in KR addition diagram to be 
\begin_inset Formula $y'=y+2\xi$
\end_inset

 , the first moment of splitting function does not satisfy the polynomiality
 which asks
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{-1}^{1}dyyf(y,\xi,t)=A(t)+(2\xi)^{2}D(t)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For KR diagram, the first moment should be 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{-1}^{1}dyyf(y,\xi,t)$
\end_inset

 in compare with gravitational form factor result.
 Then convolution formula will be 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{-1}^{1}dy\frac{1}{y}f(y,\xi,t)H(\frac{x}{y},\frac{\xi}{y},t)$
\end_inset

.
 But now the range of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $[-2\xi,1-\xi]$
\end_inset

 in KR additional diagram, and 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1+\xi]$
\end_inset

 in normal KR diagram which is not allowed in this form.
\end_layout

